#Text=Marsha I. Lester
#Text=Marsha Isack
#Text=Lester
#Text=is an American physical chemist .
#Text=She is currently the Edmund J. Kahn Distinguished Professor of Chemistry at the University of Pennsylvania . [ 1 ]
#Text=Lester uses both theoretical and experimental methods to study the physical chemistry of volatile organic compounds present in the earth 's atmosphere .
#Text=Her current work focuses on the hydroxyl radical and Criegee intermediates .
#Text=Education
#Text=Lester graduated with a B.A. from Douglass Residential College , an institution for women within Rutgers University , in 1976 .
#Text=She then earned her Ph.D. from Columbia University in 1981 in the laboratory of George Flynn .
#Text=Her thesis was entitled Vibrational Relaxation Dynamics in Bulk Gases and Supersonic Molecular Beams . [ 2 ]
#Text=She carried out postdoctoral work as a National Science Foundation Fellow at Bell Laboratories from 1981 to 1982 . [ 1 ]
#Text=Career
#Text=Currently she works as a professor at University of Pennsylvania [ 1 ] from which she has received the Edmund J. and Louise W. Kahn Award in the Natural Sciences .
#Text=Lester was the first female chair of the Department of Chemistry , a position she held from 2005 to 2009 . [ 3 ] [ 4 ]
#Text=She was a founder , and is currently chair , of the Penn Forum for Women Faculty , a group formed to support female faculty at the university . [ 4 ]
#Text=Lester is also well known as the editor of the Journal of Chemical Physics . [ 5 ]
#Text=Previously , Lester was the chair of the Division of Laser Science of the American Physical Society .
#Text=She also worked for American Chemical Society .
#Text=Later on , she was the chair of the Department of Energy 's Council for Chemical and Biochemical Sciences .
#Text=Research
#Text=Lester 's research group utilizes theoretical and experimental approaches to study chemical reactions .
#Text=She focuses on modeling potential energy surfaces between reactive partners , with an emphasis on volatile organic compounds present in the earth 's atmosphere .
#Text=She has published extensively on the interactions and reactions of the hydroxyl radical . [ 6 ]
#Text=Lester 's group was the first to obtain an infrared spectrum of the hydrogen trioxide radical .
#Text=Her lab currently works on modeling the stability of this radical and its conformers . [ 1 ]
#Text=Currently , her group focuses on photo-induced chemistry of Criegee intermediates , an intermediate in the alkene ozonolysis pathway .
#Text=This pathway is a primary oxidation pathway for alkenes in the troposphere and generates atmospheric hydroxyl radicals .
#Text=Her lab synthesizes Criegee intermediates in order to further study their chemical reactions using spectroscopy . [ 1 ]
#Text=Her lab also currently focuses on modeling and observing the collisional quenching of excited hydroxyl radicals .
#Text=Quenching impacts the concentration of hydroxyl radicals in the atmosphere , and is therefore of environmental interest .
#Text=Her research group at the University of Pennsylvania was behind the development of open shell complexes .
